00:54.220 --> 00:57.656
Hey! Darce.

01:01.227 --> 01:03.062
Look, you shouldn't be
out here either.

01:03.064 --> 01:06.198
Too many people come out
at the same time,

01:06.200 --> 01:07.366
she's gonna bust us.

01:07.368 --> 01:09.368
And then what?
- Mmm?

01:09.370 --> 01:10.803
No more gardening at night.

01:10.805 --> 01:13.405
Hey, you know how that
cramps your style.

01:13.407 --> 01:16.608
Well, I got these roses
on sale at Walmart today.

01:16.610 --> 01:19.211
I get 'em in the ground
while the soil's cooled off,

01:19.213 --> 01:20.279
else they're gonna wither.

01:20.281 --> 01:23.182
Serves you right if they wither,
shopping at Walmart.

01:23.184 --> 01:25.818
You want me to make coffee in
the morning or you gonna do it?

01:25.820 --> 01:29.855
Me. I'll see you at 7:00.
Get some sleep.

01:29.857 --> 01:31.490
It's too hot.

01:49.709 --> 01:52.744
Agh, it already feels like
i switched the blow dryer

01:52.746 --> 01:55.147
on "high" and held it up
to my face for half an hour.

01:55.149 --> 01:57.483
It doesn't help that
you're driving around

01:57.485 --> 01:58.417
in a mini sweat lodge.

01:58.419 --> 01:59.718
<i>Hello, folks.</i>

01:59.720 --> 02:01.887
<i>Today we're heading into
our 88th consecutive day</i>

02:01.889 --> 02:04.323
<i>of no rain here
in north Georgia in this,</i>

02:04.325 --> 02:06.525
<i>the hottest September
on record.</i>

02:06.527 --> 02:08.594
<i>And there's no rain in sight.</i>

02:10.131 --> 02:10.795
Oh, shit, space cowboy.

02:10.798 --> 02:13.298
Don't look, don't look,
don't look, don't look.

02:13.300 --> 02:15.167
What?
He knows your truck.

02:15.169 --> 02:17.803
Don't make eye contact.
Christ.

02:17.805 --> 02:20.606
He's never awake
this time of...

02:20.608 --> 02:22.875
hey, Clay, how you doing?

02:51.304 --> 02:54.706
Do you have a second, Darcy?

02:54.708 --> 02:55.774
I don't want to alarm you,

02:55.776 --> 02:57.809
because there is nothing
to worry about yet,

02:57.811 --> 03:01.647
but the Dean's been discussing
budget cuts and layoffs again,

03:01.649 --> 03:04.683
and we may have to pare down
on administrative assistants.

03:04.685 --> 03:05.817
Uh-huh.

03:05.819 --> 03:08.187
I know you were interested
in a tuition option

03:08.189 --> 03:10.422
after two years of service.
- Right.

03:10.424 --> 03:13.358
Did you get
your application in?

03:13.360 --> 03:15.227
Good, ma in American lit.

03:15.229 --> 03:17.829
Ba. Ba.
I never got my degree.

03:17.831 --> 03:20.532
Well, good for you
for finishing it now.

03:20.534 --> 03:24.836
Oh, also, you may have to pay
in more to the health plan.

03:24.838 --> 03:27.673
You don't have
any dependents, correct?

03:29.642 --> 03:31.243
No.

03:31.245 --> 03:33.478
So they need you
to get out there

03:33.480 --> 03:35.314
and find the money
and be all charming,

03:35.316 --> 03:37.783
so you're totally safe,
and geri,

03:37.785 --> 03:40.452
you know everything there is
to know about computers.

03:40.454 --> 03:41.687
Plus not to be blunt,

03:41.689 --> 03:43.855
but you got race <i> and</i> gender
on your side.

03:43.857 --> 03:46.692
Funny how things work out sometimes.
- Shut up.

03:46.694 --> 03:48.660
I think it'll be fine, darce.
Don't stress.

03:48.662 --> 03:51.763
You could always ask Clayton
for your old job back.

03:51.765 --> 03:52.831
No. No, no, no.

03:52.833 --> 03:55.601
No, she was the world's
worst waitress.

03:55.603 --> 03:56.835
No.
- Oh.

03:56.837 --> 04:00.339
I'll see you after work,
sweetheart.

04:00.341 --> 04:02.007
Love you.

04:35.608 --> 04:37.976
oh, pardon me.
- Sorry.

04:37.978 --> 04:41.380
Oh. Oh.

04:41.382 --> 04:43.649
Are you...

04:43.651 --> 04:45.951
is that Kevin?
Kevin Jenkins?

04:45.953 --> 04:48.754
Miss baylor,
how you been keeping?

04:51.058 --> 04:52.524
Fine.

04:52.526 --> 04:53.792
I'm sorry, Kevin.

04:53.794 --> 04:57.362
I... I almost didn't
recognize you.

04:57.364 --> 05:01.033
You just...
Look so different.

05:01.035 --> 05:02.734
This here is my wife, Beth.

05:02.736 --> 05:05.971
Oh, excuse me.
I'm Darcy, Darcy baylor.

05:05.973 --> 05:08.073
Kevin was friends
with my son Walker.

05:08.075 --> 05:10.575
They had some run together,
those two.

05:10.577 --> 05:11.777
Yep.

05:11.779 --> 05:15.080
From kindergarten all the way
through to grad school.

05:15.082 --> 05:16.615
They were thick as thieves.

05:16.617 --> 05:19.885
Kevin told me all about it.
Such a loss.

05:19.887 --> 05:21.687
I can't
imagine how painful...

05:21.689 --> 05:22.821
this your first?

05:22.823 --> 05:25.557
We've got three boys
already.

05:25.559 --> 05:26.625
This is a boy, too.

05:26.627 --> 05:30.629
Aren't you a little young
to have that many kids, Kevin?

05:30.631 --> 05:33.799
I'm almost 32, Ms. baylor.

05:37.003 --> 05:39.738
We're up from Birmingham
visiting mama.

05:39.740 --> 05:42.841
I run an accounting firm
down there now, so.

05:42.843 --> 05:45.010
Well,
you remember me to her.

05:45.012 --> 05:46.845
Yes, ma'am, of course.

06:55.782 --> 06:58.083
here you go, zipper.

07:09.462 --> 07:10.829
Hey.
- Hey.

07:10.831 --> 07:14.099
Want to come over?
I'm fixing a salad.

07:14.101 --> 07:15.066
<i>I can't, working late.</i>

07:15.068 --> 07:16.935
Dean says the funding letter's
gotta go out,

07:16.937 --> 07:19.171
and I'm up to my eyeballs
trying to track down

07:19.173 --> 07:20.806
any alum that's got money.

07:20.808 --> 07:23.208
Mm, donations
are in short supply, huh?

07:23.210 --> 07:24.643
<i>Mostly, but I just found</i>

07:24.645 --> 07:26.478
one prospect who's loaded,
apparently.

07:26.480 --> 07:29.581
Wasn't Walker friends
with some guy named mark Wright?

07:29.583 --> 07:31.082
Mark Wright.

07:31.084 --> 07:34.886
Oh, he's from
New Orleans originally?

07:34.888 --> 07:36.855
The very one.

07:36.857 --> 07:37.589
Yeah.

07:37.591 --> 07:39.758
He and Walker were in
business school together.

07:39.760 --> 07:44.062
I never liked that kid.
He had weird-ass energy.

07:44.064 --> 07:48.700
Huh, so, what can you tell me
about mark Wright?

07:48.702 --> 07:50.535
<i>I don't know.</i>

07:50.537 --> 07:54.906
Walker kind of idolized him.
I could never figure out why.

07:54.908 --> 07:57.843
He was from some rich family.
Yeah.

07:57.845 --> 08:00.912
He was dealing coke all over.
Not like he had to.

08:00.914 --> 08:04.216
But nobody ever bothered him
about it

08:04.218 --> 08:07.118
'cause he was a legacy.

08:07.920 --> 08:10.222
Did you see that?
Heat lightning.

08:10.224 --> 08:11.490
<i>It's a big fat tease.</i>

08:11.492 --> 08:17.028
Not like we're getting any
actual precipitation out of it.

08:17.030 --> 08:20.165
Anyway, mark was always
hiring Walker

08:20.167 --> 08:24.536
to do shit jobs like pick up
his dry cleaning

08:24.538 --> 08:26.137
because he knew
he was hard up for cash.

08:26.139 --> 08:28.640
Well, you know what they say.
Money begets money.

08:28.642 --> 08:31.877
<i>Mark Wright's worth something
like 5 million bucks now.</i>

08:31.879 --> 08:33.278
What?
-<i> Made it all in this chain</i>

08:33.280 --> 08:35.013
of restaurants down
in Louisiana.

08:35.015 --> 08:37.649
You shaving your legs or something?
- No.

08:37.650 --> 08:39.918
<i>What kind of restaurant?</i>
- Oh, it's ridiculous.

08:39.919 --> 08:41.852
It's like make
your own hot dogs,

08:41.855 --> 08:45.190
dogs the way you want them,
something like that.

08:45.192 --> 08:46.691
Hot dogs.

08:46.693 --> 08:47.259
<i>Yeah.</i>

08:47.261 --> 08:50.228
Like ones made
with all-natural ingredients,

08:50.230 --> 08:53.064
<i>and some of them
are vegetarian?</i>

08:53.066 --> 08:54.566
Uh-huh.
-<i> Like tofu?</i>

08:54.568 --> 08:57.936
Uh-huh.
- Is it called the dawg house?

08:57.938 --> 09:00.005
Like d-a-w-g?

09:00.007 --> 09:03.775
Yeah, d-a-w-g.
How'd you know that?

09:06.045 --> 09:09.180
<i>Darce?
Are you still there?</i>

09:11.617 --> 09:13.018
I gotta go.

09:51.324 --> 09:53.224
Hey.

09:58.931 --> 10:01.866
Last time I saw that look
on your face,

10:01.868 --> 10:04.970
it was the night that you broke
that menu board

10:04.972 --> 10:08.039
over some guy's head
when he grabbed your ass

10:08.041 --> 10:10.742
when you set down
his meatloaf.

10:12.044 --> 10:14.613
I was in the stock room
minding my own business,

10:14.615 --> 10:17.916
and I heard "cr-ack."

10:17.918 --> 10:20.318
Cleaved it clean in two.

10:28.961 --> 10:29.394
Darcy?

10:29.396 --> 10:32.263
If you didn't want to see me,
what you come in here for?

10:32.265 --> 10:36.368
It's good to get out
of the house sometimes.

10:37.770 --> 10:41.973
Byrd told me you're worried
about your job.

10:41.975 --> 10:43.708
Town crier.

10:45.211 --> 10:48.747
Are you going to quit
being cryptic or what?

11:53.045 --> 11:57.749
Remember when you, me,
and Walker dug this bed?

11:57.751 --> 11:59.417
I do.

12:00.152 --> 12:02.954
He's been coming up
all day today.

12:02.956 --> 12:06.891
Some days, you know,
he just sort of surfaces.

12:06.893 --> 12:09.127
Some days not at all.

12:11.330 --> 12:14.032
When he was real little
and I barely had

12:14.034 --> 12:15.500
two pennies to rub together,

12:15.502 --> 12:19.104
there was one thing
we would always do on Saturdays,

12:19.106 --> 12:22.941
and that was walk up to Louie's
and get hot dogs.

12:22.943 --> 12:25.376
I'd get two everythings.

12:25.378 --> 12:26.344
He'd get a chili dog.

12:26.346 --> 12:31.049
We'd both get lemonades,
and then we'd walk home.

12:31.051 --> 12:33.151
It didn't matter what it was
like out weather-wise.

12:33.153 --> 12:38.356
Eating our hot dogs, you know,
talking about this and that.

12:38.358 --> 12:39.524
Even in the rain.

12:39.526 --> 12:44.028
We considered it good luck
to eat a hot dog in the rain.

12:45.331 --> 12:48.867
Once Walker got done
with his lemonade,

12:48.869 --> 12:53.037
he'd hold my hand
up till he was around 10 or so,

12:53.039 --> 12:54.372
and then he quit.

12:54.374 --> 12:56.474
Well,
the time's gonna come

12:56.476 --> 13:00.044
when a boy eventually lets go
of his mama's hand.

13:02.782 --> 13:09.020
When he was getting
his business plan together

13:09.022 --> 13:10.088
for grad school,

13:10.090 --> 13:13.424
he wanted to start a chain
of family restaurants

13:13.426 --> 13:15.059
where you can make
your own hot dog,

13:15.061 --> 13:18.163
and I thought to myself,
i took this child to museums

13:18.165 --> 13:20.231
and read him good books
and paid for cello lessons,

13:20.233 --> 13:22.300
and all he's hanging onto
is the hot dogs.

13:22.302 --> 13:26.971
Well, he had his own ideas
about what he wanted to do.

13:27.873 --> 13:31.009
He worked the whole thing out,
real detailed.

13:31.011 --> 13:35.814
I know, 'cause
i typed it up for him.

13:35.816 --> 13:38.116
And then his professor
handed it back

13:38.118 --> 13:40.485
and told him that business plan
was never gonna fly.

13:40.487 --> 13:45.089
Was that the professor
you stared at real hard

13:45.091 --> 13:48.293
when he parked his Honda
by the light downtown and then,

13:48.295 --> 13:52.463
poof, his engine died?

13:55.367 --> 13:59.537
Yeah.
He was only 24.

14:00.940 --> 14:04.909
If I could've gotten him
over that hump.

14:04.911 --> 14:10.281
If... if I could've
just helped him...

14:10.283 --> 14:11.216
Get a little further.

14:11.218 --> 14:13.952
If he even made it to 30,
he would've been okay.

14:13.954 --> 14:16.955
I know.
I know you believe that.

14:16.957 --> 14:23.595
But you just gotta quit blaming
yourself eventually, baby.

14:53.225 --> 14:55.026
Mm.

14:55.527 --> 14:56.494
Here.

14:56.496 --> 14:59.097
Oh,<i> that</i> asshole.

14:59.099 --> 15:00.431
Oh, yeah, that guy.

15:00.433 --> 15:02.400
You know, he used to come
into the bar

15:02.402 --> 15:05.403
and try and order expensive
bottles of champagne

15:05.405 --> 15:07.338
he knew damn well
we didn't carry.

15:07.340 --> 15:09.007
He drove by in his Audi
blasting rap music

15:09.009 --> 15:11.609
and hollering at Walker
when he was cutting your grass.

15:11.611 --> 15:16.581
I forgot all about that.
Watch those crumbs, Clay.

15:16.583 --> 15:17.348
Honey, I mean,

15:17.350 --> 15:21.052
even if he stole Walker's idea,
you can't prove it.

15:21.054 --> 15:24.289
If I can find a copy of Walker's
old business plan, I can.

15:24.291 --> 15:26.190
What are you gonna do?
You gonna sue him?

15:26.192 --> 15:27.525
You want his money?

15:27.527 --> 15:28.993
That's not what I want.

15:28.995 --> 15:31.396
Why not?
You could use it.

15:31.398 --> 15:32.931
Maybe.

15:32.933 --> 15:35.700
That's not what I'm after.

15:35.702 --> 15:39.170
When byrd called me,
it was like something...

15:39.172 --> 15:44.242
I don't know, I don't know
how to describe it.

15:44.244 --> 15:48.046
It was like something
filled up this room.

15:48.048 --> 15:50.481
It was pushing at the walls,

15:50.483 --> 15:54.218
like they were vibrating
or something.

15:54.220 --> 15:58.222
I felt Walker's presence
in here so strong.

15:58.224 --> 16:03.428
I hadn't felt that way
since the night he died.

16:03.430 --> 16:08.399
Every molecule of me
was alive to him.

16:10.336 --> 16:11.569
He was calling to me.

16:11.571 --> 16:16.741
What else can I do
except try to answer?

16:31.056 --> 16:33.024
Darcy baylor.
My, what a surprise.

16:33.026 --> 16:35.727
Hey, sue Anne, your yard's
sure looking gorgeous.

16:35.729 --> 16:39.530
Aren't you worried about getting
ticketed for the sprinklers?

16:39.532 --> 16:41.599
Oh, we aren't
on water restrictions

16:41.601 --> 16:43.001
here in the heights.

16:43.003 --> 16:44.369
What can I help you with,
Darcy?

16:44.371 --> 16:47.205
Well, actually,
I'm looking for Kevin.

16:47.207 --> 16:49.007
Well, he and Beth
and the boys

16:49.009 --> 16:50.742
headed back to Alabama
around dawn.

16:50.744 --> 16:54.479
I need to speak with him
about something.

16:54.481 --> 16:57.648
Maybe you could just give me
his number then.

16:58.584 --> 17:01.719
Um, try "zipper."

17:02.454 --> 17:04.288
That's not it either.

17:04.290 --> 17:05.522
What about "interpol"?

17:05.525 --> 17:06.391
Some kind of joke?

17:06.393 --> 17:10.328
It's the name
of his favorite band.

17:10.329 --> 17:11.429
Mm-mm.

17:11.431 --> 17:12.663
"Asimov."

17:12.665 --> 17:16.034
What? What?
- "Asimov."

17:16.036 --> 17:16.434
Uh-uh.

17:16.435 --> 17:20.704
There's got to be some kind
of code you can crack.

17:20.707 --> 17:23.574
It's encrypted,
i mean, you gotta figure out

17:23.576 --> 17:25.042
the password he
would've used, Darcy.

17:25.045 --> 17:28.212
Otherwise nothing I can do.
- "Periwinkle."

17:28.214 --> 17:29.047
"Periwinkle"?

17:29.049 --> 17:32.316
You sure you don't
have a single hard copy

17:32.318 --> 17:33.217
of that thing anywhere?

17:33.219 --> 17:36.687
Those aren't the kinds
of things i held onto.

17:46.098 --> 17:47.165
Cinnamon roll.
- Yeah.

17:47.167 --> 17:50.134
Look, I'll cut to the chase, Clay.
- Okay.

17:50.136 --> 17:52.637
I need that thing you been
holding for me.

17:52.639 --> 17:54.605
I'm sorry, what thing?

17:54.607 --> 17:57.375
That bag.

17:58.477 --> 17:59.844
From the police.

17:59.846 --> 18:03.081
Why do you need that
right now?

18:04.516 --> 18:07.085
I just feel like
maybe it's time.

18:07.087 --> 18:09.554
Time to use what's in
the bag?

18:09.556 --> 18:13.491
It's just I'm ready
to take it back now.

18:15.127 --> 18:16.594
Yeah?

18:18.564 --> 18:20.631
I don't think so.

18:20.633 --> 18:25.837
You do know that it's my job
to protect you from you.

18:25.839 --> 18:30.274
In fact, I could make it
my full-time vocation.

18:30.276 --> 18:32.643
Please.

18:32.645 --> 18:34.846
Just give it to me.

18:56.902 --> 18:58.636
Stop!
You stop right there!

18:58.638 --> 19:01.639
I'm calling the cops!
You're trespassing!

19:01.641 --> 19:02.773
Sorry, i-i-i...

19:02.775 --> 19:05.276
Who are you?!
What're you doing here?!

19:05.278 --> 19:06.277
My name's Darcy baylor.

19:06.279 --> 19:09.614
I just... I knew somebody
who used to live in this house.

19:09.616 --> 19:13.484
Whoa.
Walker's mom?

19:14.153 --> 19:19.457
So when mark moved out,
his dad let me stay on.

19:19.459 --> 19:20.758
Figure they got so much money,

19:20.760 --> 19:24.495
forgot they even owned
the place, you know?

19:24.497 --> 19:29.467
Some accountant pays
the taxes once a year.

19:29.469 --> 19:30.635
It's all good.

19:30.637 --> 19:34.372
You got some needle and thread,
i could mend that for you.

19:36.542 --> 19:38.509
You still talk to mark?

19:38.511 --> 19:41.812
No, nope, we're not in touch.

19:46.852 --> 19:48.452
Dennis?

19:48.454 --> 19:50.655
I need you to think back

19:50.657 --> 19:55.193
to around the time that...
that Walker died.

19:57.796 --> 20:01.399
About how he was acting,
how mark was acting,

20:01.401 --> 20:05.937
what might've been going on
between those two.

20:07.673 --> 20:10.474
Dennis.

20:12.544 --> 20:13.377
I don't know.

20:13.379 --> 20:16.614
There weren't any bad vibes
or anything.

20:16.616 --> 20:17.281
Uh-huh.

20:17.283 --> 20:19.217
I'd have picked up on it
if there was.

20:19.219 --> 20:20.685
Yeah, of course.
- You know?

20:20.687 --> 20:25.256
I mean, Walker was kind of
a mess that day, but...

20:25.258 --> 20:27.758
wait, what day?

20:27.760 --> 20:28.793
Well...

20:28.795 --> 20:31.295
You know, the day he, uh...

20:31.297 --> 20:33.764
Walker came out here
the day he died?

20:33.766 --> 20:34.732
Yeah.

20:34.734 --> 20:37.001
Well, how come none of you boys
ever told me that?

20:37.003 --> 20:39.904
You never asked.
Why are you asking now?

20:39.906 --> 20:41.772
It's been, what,
six years or something?

20:41.774 --> 20:44.575
Seven.
Just tell me.

20:46.245 --> 20:47.979
Okay.

20:50.482 --> 20:52.416
Well...

20:52.418 --> 20:53.884
I remember it was hot,

20:53.886 --> 20:56.654
hot and dry
like it's been lately.

20:56.656 --> 21:00.625
Walker dragged his ass
all the way in from town.

21:00.627 --> 21:03.361
Tried to hitch,
but nobody'd pick him up.

21:03.363 --> 21:05.930
That's why he had
the blisters.

21:05.932 --> 21:08.466
And when Walker got here,

21:08.468 --> 21:12.270
he and mark went back
into mark's room.

21:12.272 --> 21:14.305
They were doing lines.

21:14.307 --> 21:15.606
I guess.

21:15.608 --> 21:16.440
Come on, Dennis.

21:16.442 --> 21:19.944
Mark, he always had it,
you know?

21:20.846 --> 21:23.748
But the weird thing was,

21:23.750 --> 21:27.718
when Walker came out
of mark's room, he had...

21:29.054 --> 21:31.022
What?

21:32.791 --> 21:36.027
He had... he had a box
of bullets in his hand.

23:09.755 --> 23:11.789
